Introduction¶

Wine certification is generally assessed by physicochemical and sensory tests . Physicochemical laboratory tests routinely used to characterize wine include determination of density, alcohol or pH values, while sensory tests rely mainly on human experts. It should be stressed that taste is the least understood of the human senses thus wine classification is a difficult task. Moreover, There are numerous factors that may impact the quality of red wine and white wine.so it will be a gigantic challenge to Find the biggest contributors.

This report is organized as follows:

  • Overview section describes the dataset used and the features in this dataset.
  • Data Preparation section covers data cleaning and data preparation steps.
  • Data Exploration section explores dataset features and their inter-relationships.
  • Statistical Modeling and Performance Evaluation section fits multiple linear regression models and performs diagnostic checks.
  • Summary and Conclusions section provides a summary of our methodology and presents our findings.
  • Reference

Overview¶

Data source¶

For this project, we have selected our dataset from Wine Quality Data Set at https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/Wine+Quality ,It has been compiled by Paulo Cortez,Antnio Cerdeira, Fernando Almeida,Telmo Matos,Jos Reis. data repository available on the https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0167923609001377?via%3Dihub (November 2009).

Objective¶

Our aim is to determine which factors have the most impact on quality of wine (whether the effect is positive or negative). As there are various factors, we will do an analysis on a few selected variables, and see which one has the biggest effect on wine. Finding the variable with the largest impact on wine, out of all the possible variables, may require a bigger and more extensive report, than is required at this time.

Response variable¶

Out of the descriptive features, we have chosen the quality of wine as our response variable / target feature. It is a continuous numerical variable, so we are able to conduct several linear regression models and graphs on it. quality of wine: quality measure in wine: continuous

Descriptive Features¶

  • fixed acidity
  • volatile acidity
  • citric acid
  • residual sugar
  • chlorides
  • free sulfur dioxide
  • total sulfur dioxide
  • density
  • pH
  • sulphates

  • alcohol

    Output variable (based on sensory data):

  • quality (score between 0 and 10)

#specifying the attribute names
attributeNames = [
   'fixed acidity',
   'volatile acidity',
   'citric acid',
   'residual sugar',
   'chlorides',
   'free sulfur dioxide',
   'total sulfur dioxide',
   'density',
   'pH',
   'sulphates',
   'alcohol',
   'quality',

#Read in data
winequality_white = pd.read_csv('winequality-white.csv',sep=';',names = attributeNames)
winequality_red = pd.read_csv('winequality-red.csv',sep=';',names = attributeNames)

#Join the two datasets together
winequality = pd.concat([winequality_white,winequality_red])

#Display randomly selected 10 rows
winequality.sample(10,random_state=999)

Fixing Column Names¶

Some column names contain a space, which can be problematic when modeling. Basically, when we write the regression formula. So, we modify the column names so that the space are replaced with an underscore sign.

In [54]:

                        'volatile acidity':'volatile_aciditys',
                        'citric acid':'citric_acid',
                        'residual sugar':'residual_sugar',

                           'total sulfur dioxide':'total_sulfur_dioxide'}, inplace = True)

Statistical Modeling and Performance Evaluation¶

Full Model¶

We begin by fitting a multiple linear regression that predicts the relationship between each indenpendent variable to dependentquality using all of the avaliable features. We call this the full model. First let's take a quick peak at the clean data.

Models:

  • quality and fixed acidity
  • quality and volatile acidity
  • quality and citric acid
  • quality and residual sugar
  • quality and chlorides
  • quality and free sulfur dioxide
  • quality and total sulfur dioxide
  • quality and density
  • quality and pH
  • quality and sulphates
  • quality and alcohol
  • Full Model
  • Backwards Variable Selection

Backwards Variable Selection¶

We now perform backwards variable selection using p-values.

In [119]:
## create the patsy model desc from formula
my_linreg_patsy = patsy.ModelDesc.from_formula(formula_string)
###
# initialize variable-selected fit to full model
linreg_fit = model_fitted
#########
## do backwards elimination using p-values
p_val_cutoff = 0.05
for i in range(len(linreg_fit.model.exog_names)):
    pval_series = linreg_fit.pvalues.copy()
    pval_series.sort_values(ascending=False, inplace=True)
    term = pval_series.index[0]
    pval = pval_series[0]
    if (pval < p_val_cutoff):
        break
    print(f"iteration: {i}, removing term: {term}, p-value: {pval:.3f}")
    terms = term.split(':')
    if (len(terms) == 1): ## this is a main effect term
        my_linreg_patsy.rhs_termlist.remove(patsy.Term([patsy.EvalFactor(term)]))    
    else: ## this is an interaction term
        my_linreg_patsy.rhs_termlist.remove(patsy.Term([patsy.EvalFactor(terms[0]), patsy.EvalFactor(terms[1])]))    
    linreg_fit = smf.ols(formula = my_linreg_patsy, data = df).fit()
#########

###
## this is the clean fit after backwards elimination
model_reduced_fitted = smf.ols(formula = my_linreg_patsy, data = winequality).fit()
###
    
#########

Summary and Conclusions¶

In this project, our goal is to find out how those given input attributes affect the output of wine quality from cilent. Although the taste of wine quality is subjective, but it is affected by some physicochemical and sensory tests objectively.

Reduced Model:quality and predicted quality The reduced Model shows there is a positive linear relationship between the Actual quality and Predicted, and the model is reasonably fitted. The adjusted R-Squared value is 0.200, meaning that 20.00% of the variance is described in the model. Regarding to coefficients, there are quite a few p-values that are not significant. These include: density,chlorides,volatile_aciditys,citric_acid.There are only a few outliers in this model, the largest ones are observed to be positive residuals which reside between 3 and 4 && 8 and 9 along the y axis. It is also abserved that the actual life expetancy is slightly left skewed.

Full Model Diagnostic Checks From the scatterplot, it is observed that the majority of the plots reside between -1.2 and 1.5, which makes the model valid. However there are some outliers, the largest outlier is a negative residual between 4 and 6 along the x axis and it is just above 2on the y axis, the second largest outlier is a positive residual below 50 along the x axis and exactly on 10 on the y axis. Apart from these outliers, the points are generally centred on 0. As a result only 1 variables were used -alcohol. The p-value of the reduced model is 0.0, meaning the coefficients used are significant.

Residuals The full model and the reduced model have similar residuals. The the most significant outliers in this model are in between the same intervals as the full model 5, there are some positive residuals and 8, there is one major negative residual.

Probability Polt From the histogram the residuals are approximately normal.

To conclude, no matter what is white or red wine, the quality is mostly depends on sulphates and pH that indirectly affect the customer's taste and product sells.
